units. Also provided are conversion factors to convert metric units to U.S. standard units.

c0: Corrosion prevention and control of Army materiel is a continuing concern.
content: Corrosion prevention and control of Army materiel is a continuing concern. It is important that any corrosion

c0: problems with this item be reported so that the problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to
content: problems with this item be reported so that the problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to

c0: prevent the problem in future items.
content: prevent the problem in future items. The term "corrosion" means the deterioration of a material or its properties

c0: due to a reaction of that materiel with its chemical environment.
content: due to a reaction of that materiel with its chemical environment. An example is the rusting of iron. Corrosion

c0: damage in metals can be seen, depending on the metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or
content: damage in metals can be seen, depending on the metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or
cracking. Plastics, composites, and rubbers can also degrade (also considered to be corrosion based on the

c0: above definition of corrosion). Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents),
content: above definition of corrosion). Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents),
or photolytic (light, typically ultraviolet) processes. The most common exposures are excessive heat or light.

c0: Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking.
content: Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking. The US Army has

c0: defined the following nine (9) forms of corrosion used to evaluate the deterioration of metals.
content: defined the following nine (9) forms of corrosion used to evaluate the deterioration of metals. These shall be used

c0: UNIFORM (or general attack): Affects a large area of exposed metal surface, like rust on steel or tarnish
content: UNIFORM (or general attack): Affects a large area of exposed metal surface, like rust on steel or tarnish
on silver. It gradually reduces the thickness of the metal until it fails.

c0: CREVICE: Occurs in crevices created by rubber seals, gaskets, bolt heads, lap joints, dirt or other surface
content: CREVICE: Occurs in crevices created by rubber seals, gaskets, bolt heads, lap joints, dirt or other surface
deposits. It will develop anywhere moisture or other corrosive agents are trapped and unable to drain or

c0: SELECTIVE LEACHING: One element, usually the anodic element of an alloy, corrodes away, leaving
content: SELECTIVE LEACHING: One element, usually the anodic element of an alloy, corrodes away, leaving
the cathodic element. This can create holes in metal.

c0: INTERGRANULAR: Metal deterioration caused by corrosion on the bonds between or across the grain
content: INTERGRANULAR: Metal deterioration caused by corrosion on the bonds between or across the grain
boundaries of the metal. The metal will appear to be peeling off in sheets, flaking, or being pushed apart
by layers. A particular type of intergranular corrosion is exfoliation.

c0: PITTING: This can result from conditions similar to those for crevice corrosion.
content: PITTING: This can result from conditions similar to those for crevice corrosion. Pits can develop on

c0: various materials due to their composition.
content: various materials due to their composition. Rifle boxes are big victims of pitting.

c0: EROSION: Results when a moving fluid (liquid or gas) flows across a metal surface, particularly when
content: EROSION: Results when a moving fluid (liquid or gas) flows across a metal surface, particularly when

c0: solid particles are present in the fluid.
content: solid particles are present in the fluid. Corrosion actually occurs on the surface of the metal, but the

c0: moving fluid washes away the corrosion and exposes a new metal surface, which also corrodes.
content: moving fluid washes away the corrosion and exposes a new metal surface, which also corrodes.

c0: FRETTING: Occurs as a result of small, repetitive movements (e.g., vibration) between two surfaces in
content: FRETTING: Occurs as a result of small, repetitive movements (e.g., vibration) between two surfaces in
contact with each other. It's usually identified by a black powder corrosion product or pits on the surface.

c0: GALVANIC: Occurs when two different types of metal come in contact with each other, like steel bolts on
content: GALVANIC: Occurs when two different types of metal come in contact with each other, like steel bolts on
aluminum, for example. This is a common problem on aircraft because of their mix of metals.

c0: STRESS: Term used to describe corrosion cracking and corrosion fatigue.
content: STRESS: Term used to describe corrosion cracking and corrosion fatigue.

c0: Where an item is not ready/available due to one of these forms of corrosion, it shall be recorded as a corrosion
content: Where an item is not ready/available due to one of these forms of corrosion, it shall be recorded as a corrosion

c0: failure in the inspection record and the appropriate code (170) for corrosion shall be used when requesting/
content: failure in the inspection record and the appropriate code (170) for corrosion shall be used when requesting/

title: Chapter 4 - PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE CHECKS AND SERVICES (PMCS) FOR RIGID INFLATABLE BOAT (RIB)
PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE CHECKS AND SERVICES (PMCS) INTRODUCTION
PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE CHECKS AND SERVICES (PMCS)

c0: To ensure the Rigid Inflatable Boat (RIB) is ready for operation at all times, it must be inspected on a regular
content: To ensure the Rigid Inflatable Boat (RIB) is ready for operation at all times, it must be inspected on a regular

c0: basis to find and correct problems before they result in damage, failure, or injury to personnel.
content: basis to find and correct problems before they result in damage, failure, or injury to personnel. The Preventive

c0: Maintenance Checks and Services (PMCS) table (WP 0054) contains systematic instructions for caring,
content: Maintenance Checks and Services (PMCS) table (WP 0054) contains systematic instructions for caring,

c0: inspecting, and servicing the RIB to keep it in good condition and to prevent breakdowns.
content: inspecting, and servicing the RIB to keep it in good condition and to prevent breakdowns.
ITEM NO. : Numbers in this column are for reference. Item numbers appear in the order in which checks

c0: and services must be performed at the intervals listed.
content: and services must be performed at the intervals listed. When completing DA Form 2404, Equipment

content: Inspection and Maintenance Worksheet, include the item number for the check or service indicating a
INTERVAL : This column tells you when you must do the listed procedure. If you see rust on the item,
PMCS must be done immediately. Performing PMCS at the appropriate intervals will reduce operational

c0: problems and minimize the number of repairs and replacements:
content: problems and minimize the number of repairs and replacements:

c0: ITEM TO BE CHECKED OR SERVICED
content: ITEM TO BE CHECKED OR SERVICED : This column identifies the item to be checked or serviced.
PROCEDURE : This column gives the procedure to check or service the listed item. This procedure is

c0: necessary to know if the equipment is ready or available for use.
content: necessary to know if the equipment is ready or available for use. Carefully follow these instructions.
EQUIPMENT NOT READY / AVAILABLE IF : Information in this column tells you what faults will keep

c0: your equipment from being able to perform. "Ready" and "Available" mean the equipment is on-hand and
content: your equipment from being able to perform. "Ready" and "Available" mean the equipment is on-hand and

c0: ready to perform its mission. (See DA PAM 750-8, The Army Maintenance Management System
content: ready to perform its mission. (See DA PAM 750-8, The Army Maintenance Management System

c0: (TAMMS) User's Manual.) If check and service procedures show faults listed in this column, do not
content: (TAMMS) User's Manual.) If check and service procedures show faults listed in this column, do not
operate the equipment. Follow standard operating procedures for maintaining the equipment or reporting

c0: Always observe warnings and cautions in your PMCS table.
content: Always observe warnings and cautions in your PMCS table. Warnings and cautions appear before procedures to
which they apply. Observe warnings to prevent serious injury to yourself and others, and observe cautions to

c0: prevent your equipment from being damaged.
content: prevent your equipment from being damaged.

c0: If anything looks wrong and you can't fix it, write it on your DA Form 2404.
content: If anything looks wrong and you can't fix it, write it on your DA Form 2404. If you find something seriously wrong,

c0: Before performing preventive maintenance, read all the checks required for the applicable interval and prepare all
content: Before performing preventive maintenance, read all the checks required for the applicable interval and prepare all
the tools you will need. You'll always need a wiping rag, or two.

c0: Keep all of these general checks in mind every time you do your PMCS:
content: Keep all of these general checks in mind every time you do your PMCS:
Keep it clean : Dirt, grease, oil, and debris only get in the way and may cover up a serious problem.

c0: Clean as you work and as you go.
content: Clean as you work and as you go.
Bolts, nuts, and screws : Check for loose, missing, bent, or broken fasteners. Also look for chipped

c0: paint, bare metal, or rust around bolt heads.
content: paint, bare metal, or rust around bolt heads.
Welds : Look for loose or chipped paint, rust, or gaps where parts are welded together.

c0: Corrosion prevention and control of Army materiel is a continuing concern.
content: Corrosion prevention and control of Army materiel is a continuing concern. It is important that any corrosion

c0: problems with this item be reported so that the problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to
content: problems with this item be reported so that the problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to

c0: prevent the problem in future items.
content: prevent the problem in future items. The term "corrosion" means the deterioration of a material or its properties

c0: due to a reaction of that material with its chemical environment.
content: due to a reaction of that material with its chemical environment. An example is the rusting of iron. Corrosion

c0: damage in metals can be seen, depending on the metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or
content: damage in metals can be seen, depending on the metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or
cracking. Plastics, composites, and rubbers can also degrade (also considered to be corrosion based on the

c0: above definition of corrosion). Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents),
content: above definition of corrosion). Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents),
or photolytic (light, typically ultraviolet) processes. The most common exposures are excessive heat or light.

c0: Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking.
content: Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking. The US Army has

c0: defined the following nine (9) forms of corrosion used to evaluate the deterioration of metals.
content: defined the following nine (9) forms of corrosion used to evaluate the deterioration of metals. These shall be used

c0: UNIFORM (or general attack): Affects a large area of exposed metal surface, like rust on steel or tarnish
content: UNIFORM (or general attack): Affects a large area of exposed metal surface, like rust on steel or tarnish
on silver. It gradually reduces the thickness of the metal until it fails.

c0: CREVICE: Occurs in crevices created by rubber seals, gaskets, bolt heads, lap joints, dirt or other surface
content: CREVICE: Occurs in crevices created by rubber seals, gaskets, bolt heads, lap joints, dirt or other surface
deposits. It will develop anywhere moisture or other corrosive agents are trapped and unable to drain or

c0: SELECTIVE LEACHING: One element, usually the anodic element of an alloy, corrodes away, leaving
content: SELECTIVE LEACHING: One element, usually the anodic element of an alloy, corrodes away, leaving
the cathodic element. This can create holes in metal.

c0: INTERGRANULAR: Metal deterioration caused by corrosion on the bonds between or across the grain
content: INTERGRANULAR: Metal deterioration caused by corrosion on the bonds between or across the grain
boundaries of the metal. The metal will appear to be peeling off in sheets, flaking, or being pushed apart
by layers. A particular type of intergranular corrosion is exfoliation.

c0: PITTING: This can result from conditions similar to those for crevice corrosion.
content: PITTING: This can result from conditions similar to those for crevice corrosion. Pits can develop on

c0: various materials due to their composition.
content: various materials due to their composition. Rifle boxes are big victims of pitting.

c0: EROSION: Results when a moving fluid (liquid or gas) flows across a metal surface, particularly when
content: EROSION: Results when a moving fluid (liquid or gas) flows across a metal surface, particularly when

c0: solid particles are present in the fluid.
content: solid particles are present in the fluid. Corrosion actually occurs on the surface of the metal, but the

c0: moving fluid washes away the corrosion and exposes a new metal surface, which also corrodes.
content: moving fluid washes away the corrosion and exposes a new metal surface, which also corrodes.

c0: FRETTING: Occurs as a result of small, repetitive movements (e.g., vibration) between two surfaces in
content: FRETTING: Occurs as a result of small, repetitive movements (e.g., vibration) between two surfaces in
contact with each other. It's usually identified by a black powder corrosion product or pits on the surface.

c0: GALVANIC: Occurs when two different types of metal come in contact with each other, like steel bolts on
content: GALVANIC: Occurs when two different types of metal come in contact with each other, like steel bolts on
aluminum, for example. This is a common problem on aircraft because of their mix of metals.

c0: STRESS: Term used to describe corrosion cracking and corrosion fatigue.
content: STRESS: Term used to describe corrosion cracking and corrosion fatigue.

c0: Where an item is not ready/available due to one of these forms of corrosion, it shall be recorded as a corrosion
content: Where an item is not ready/available due to one of these forms of corrosion, it shall be recorded as a corrosion

c0: failure in the inspection record and the appropriate code (170) for corrosion shall be used when requesting/
content: failure in the inspection record and the appropriate code (170) for corrosion shall be used when requesting/

content: Components of End Item (COEI). This list is for information purposes only and is not authority to

content: Basic Issue Items (BII). These essential items are required to place the RIB in operation, operate it, and
